>>>>>>> # Your chance to guide Diabetes research
>>>>>>> ![tell us your views on diabetes research](https://diabetes-resources-
>>>>>>> ### By sharing your first-hand experience of living with or caring for
someone with diabetes in our groups, you can be sure that the research funded
by us and others produces the breakthroughs in care, treatment and prevention
>>>>>>> We are currently recruiting members for two different groups, the
Diabetes Research Steering Groups and our Grants Advisory Panel. Both roles
give you the opportunity to influence the focus of new research, and help
>>>>>>> These groups are a way to be heard by key players in research. It is
vital they are made up of people with a wide range of experiences to make sure
research benefits as many people as possible. In particular we want to hear
from members of communities that have been underrepresented in these groups,
>>>>>>> * from Bangladeshi, Pakistani, Indian, Black African, Black
>>>>>>> * that are under 30 years old
>>>>>>> * living with, or at risk of, type 2 diabetes.
>>>>>>> Find out more about each role below, or email research@diabetes.org.uk
>>>>>>> The DRSGs bring together researchers, healthcare professionals and
people with first-hand experience of diabetes to talk openly to work out what
research needs to happen to improve people’s lives. Once they know what needs
to be done, they figure out how to advance and improve research in that area.
For example, they might change how a trial is run so it is easier to take part
in, or go to research funders and get them to invest in important areas that
>>>>>>> To share your experiences of diabetes to inform discussions and guide
decisions. As a member you can talk also represent the thoughts and experience
of other people living with or affected by diabetes in the wider community. We
will support you to reach out to other people living with diabetes if you want
>>>>>>> The group meets four to six times a year, and meetings are three to
six hours long. They will all be happening virtually for now.
>>>>>>> Read the full role description (PDF 146KB) Apply now
>>>>>>> The Grants Advisory Panel is made up of people living with diabetes.
The group advise on how to spend our research budget and help scientists
decide what research to fund. Over the past decade, we have committed £61.9
million to research. In 2019, we invested over £7 million across 35 research
>>>>>>> You will be reading and scoring summaries of research ideas to let us
know how important they are. This helps to make sure we’re always funding
research that is important to people with diabetes.
>>>>>>> Normally we have two to four full day meetings a year. At the moment,
we are running up to six three-hour virtual meetings instead.
>>>>>>> Read the full role description (PDF 152KB) Apply now
